Growth model of L. monocytogenes in RTE seafood including background flora competition

Source: R/sfGrowthJameson.R
sfGrowthJameson.Rd

The sfGrowthJameson() function is used to simulate the growth of L. monocytogenes in RTE seafood, as affected by lactic acid bacteria (LAB), according to the Jameson-effect competition model published in Giménez and Dalgaard (2004) .

Usage

sfGrowthJameson(
  time,
  N0Lm,
  N0LAB,
  q0Lm,
  q0LAB,
  muLm,
  muLAB,
  MPDLm,
  MPDLAB,
  unitSize,
  gamma = 1,
  lim = 1,
  step = 1
)

Arguments

time

(h) Storage time of a pack of RTE seafood

N0Lm

(CFU) Numbers of L. monocytogenes in RTE seafood at time=0

N0LAB

(CFU) Numbers of LAB in RTE seafood at time=0

q0Lm

Initial parameter Q of the Baranyi and Roberts' model related to lag phase for L. monocytogenes at time=0

q0LAB

Initial parameter Q of the Baranyi and Roberts' model related to lag phase for LAB at time=0

muLm

(h-1) Growth rate of L. monocytogenes in RTE seafood

muLAB

(h-1) Growth rate of LAB in RTE seafood

MPDLm

(log10 CFU/g) Maximum population density of L. monocytogenes in RTE seafood

MPDLAB

(log10 CFU/g) Maximum population density of LAB in RTE seafood

unitSize

(g) Weight of the contents of an RTE seafood pack (for MPD)

gamma

Interaction parameter of the competition model. Note: if gamma=1, population 1 stops when population 2 reaches MPD. If gamma < 1, population 1 still increases when population 2 reaches MPD. If gamma > 1, population 1 decreases when population 2 reaches MPD.

lim

= 1 A parameter indicating when the competition should be considered as meaningful.

step

= 1 Integration step.

Value

a list of four elements:

N1Lm

(CFU) Numbers of L. monocytogenes at the end of storage;

N1LAB

(CFU) Numbers of LAB at the end of storage;

lnQtLm

Natural logarithm of q0 for L. monocytogenes at the end of storage;

lnQtLAB

Natural logarithm of q0 for LAB at the end of storage.

Note

For sake of speed, the function first evaluates a classical Baranyi and Roberts model without interactions. If any of the two population reaches a value greater than \(10^{(MPD - lim)}\) CFU, an expanded version of the Jameson-effect model by Giménez and Dalgaard (2004) is used. This model includes the parameter gamma proposed by Møller et al. (2013) . The function is vectorized for all parameters.

References

Giménez B, Dalgaard P (2004). “Modelling and predicting the simultaneous growth of Listeria monocytogenes and spoilage micro-organisms in cold-smoked salmon.” Journal of Applied Microbiology, 96, 96-109.

Møller COA, Ilg Y, Aabo S, Christensen BB, Dalgaard P, Hansen TB (2013). “Effect of natural microbiota on growth of Salmonella spp. in fresh pork – A predictive microbiology approach.” Food Microbiology, 34(2), 284-295. ISSN 0740-0020, doi:10.1016/j.fm.2012.10.010 .

Author

Regis Pouillot rpouillot.work@gmail.com and Laurent Guillier

Examples

library(qraLm)
iter <- 1000
set.seed(666)
vtime <- 200
vN0Lm <- 10^runif(iter, 0, 3)
vN0LAB <- 10^runif(iter, 0, 3)
vq0Lm <- exp(runif(iter, 0, 1))
vq0LAB <- exp(runif(iter, 0, 1))
vmuLm <- runif(iter, 0, 0.1)
vmuLAB <- runif(iter, 0, 0.1)
sfGrowthJameson(
  time = vtime, N0Lm = vN0Lm, N0LAB = vN0LAB,
  q0Lm = vq0Lm, q0LAB = vq0LAB,
  muLm = vmuLm, muLAB = vmuLAB,
  MPDLm = 8, MPDLAB = 7,
  unitSize = 100,
  gamma = 0.8
)
